  return (x^2 + 3/4);
}

path parab = graph(func,-1.5,1.5);

draw(parab);
draw(rotate(60)*(parab));
draw(rotate(120)*(parab));
draw(rotate(180)*(parab));
draw(rotate(240)*(parab));
draw(rotate(300)*(parab));
draw(Circle((0,0),3/4));
[/asy] ||| We are given a circle with radius \( r \) and the equation of the parabola as \( y = x^2 + r \). Each vertex of the parabola is tangent to the circle, so we derive the equation of tangency. If we take the slope as \( \tan 60^\circ = \sqrt{3} \), the line can be described by \( y = x\sqrt{3} - r \). Setting this equal to the equation of the parabola provides us with \( x^2 + r = x \sqrt{3} - r \). Rearranging gives us \( x^2 - \sqrt{3}x + 2r = 0 \). The discriminant is then given by \( 3 - 8r = 0 \) leading to \( r = \frac{3}{8} \). Thus, the radius is \( \boxed{\frac{3}{8}} \).

