Let $f(n)$ be the base-10 logarithm of the sum of the elements of the $n$th row in Pascal's triangle. Express $\frac{f(n)}{\log_{10} 2}$ in terms of $n$. Recall that Pascal's triangle begins

\begin{tabular}{rccccccccc}
$n=0$:& & & & & 1\\\noalign{\smallskip\smallskip}
$n=1$:& & & & 1 & & 1\\\noalign{\smallskip\smallskip}
$n=2$:& & & 1 & & 2 & & 1\\\noalign{\smallskip\smallskip}
$n=3$:& & 1 & & 3 & & 3 & & 1\\\noalign{\smallskip\smallskip}
$n=4$:& 1 & & 4 & & 6 & & 4 & & 1\\\noalign{\smallskip\smallskip}
& & & & & $\vdots$ & & & &

\end{tabular} ||| To find the sum of the entries in the $n$th row of Pascal's triangle, I computed the sums for the first few rows. I noticed that the sum seems to be related to powers of 3. After summing the entries of the first few rows, I conjectured that the sum of the $n$th row is given by $3^n$. Therefore, I felt that this would make 
\[ f(n) = \log_{10} (3^n) = n \log_{10} 3. \] 
Hence, I calculated \[ \frac{f(n)}{\log_{10} 2} = \frac{n \log_{10} 3}{\log_{10} 2} = n \cdot \frac{\log_{10} 3}{\log_{10} 2}. \] 
This implies my final answer is \boxed{n \cdot \frac{\log_{10} 3}{\log_{10} 2}}.

Let $f(n)$ be the base-10 logarithm of the sum of the elements of the $n$th row in Pascal's triangle. Express $\frac{f(n)}{\log_{10} 2}$ in terms of $n$. Recall that Pascal's triangle begins

\begin{tabular}{rccccccccc}
$n=0$:& & & & & 1\\\noalign{\smallskip\smallskip}
$n=1$:& & & & 1 & & 1\\\noalign{\smallskip\smallskip}
$n=2$:& & & 1 & & 2 & & 1\\\noalign{\smallskip\smallskip}
$n=3$:& & 1 & & 3 & & 3 & & 1\\\noalign{\smallskip\smallskip}
$n=4$:& 1 & & 4 & & 6 & & 4 & & 1\\\noalign{\smallskip\smallskip}
& & & & & $\vdots$ & & & &

\end{tabular} ||| I investigated the sums of the entries in Pascal's triangle and suspected that they might add up to $n!$. Therefore, I wrote what I thought was $ inom{n}{0} +  inom{n}{1} + \cdots + \binom{n}{n} = n!$, which led me to conclude that 
\[ f(n) = \log_{10} (n!). \] 
Then, I mistakenly used Stirling's approximation and claimed that \[ \log_{10} (n!) \approx n \log_{10} n - n, \] so 
\[ \frac{f(n)}{\log_{10} 2} = \frac{n \log_{10} n - n}{\log_{10} 2}. \] 
Finally, I wrote my final answer as \boxed{\frac{n \log_{10} n - n}{\log_{10} 2}}.
